Chapter 1
Cohren
0430 ITANIA time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He especially hated it because he was responsible for waking everyone else in his company. Gently getting out of his bunk, he put on his combat uniform, threw his protective vest over it, and retrieved his belongings from the locker, being careful with a particular small box. He shouldered his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Attached to it were all the things he needed, such as his breathing apparatus or his special glasses. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks. Outside, the mud and ice crunched under his boots.
He took a lighter from one pocket of his jacket and a cigarette from the other. He lit it and took a brief puff before opening the door slightly. In the past week, he had come up with various ways to wake the men and women under him. He no longer used the pre-programmed alarm clock, as it usually didn't work and only produced a faint hiss from the speakers.
“Wake them up?” Cohren turned around and saw Trainmaster Nemic approaching him.
“Yes,” answered Cohren.
“What do you plan to try this time?”
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and a few others came towards him already dressed for duty.
“Good morning,” said Craith.
“What woke you up?” asked Cohren.
“Firstly, we didn’t want to wait for whatever you might come up with today. And secondly, the shock troops, who have to get up first, should be able to choose their morning ration,” one of the men, Ravik, replied. “And you know how bad the food can be.”
“Good point, Corporal,” said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a switch. A loud, shrill alarm sounded throughout the barracks. Inside, he heard soft curses and people running around.
“Man, Valturi,” said Nemic. “I thought they would have learned by now to wake up at the same time as you.”
“Well, my guys from the training camp have learned it,” Cohren replied, pointing at Harris, Craith, and Ravik. “However, the platoon and trainee leaders also know that they have to wake up before their units.”
A few seconds later, the rest of the company came out. They had everything they needed, from personal items to the required equipment. Some of the new recruits looked confused, while others appeared irritated.
“Good morning,” said Cohren cheerfully.
“With all due respect, sir, why do you have to wake us up so early?” asked a field corporal from the assault team.
“Because the regular alarms are shit and because Daybreak won’t sleep late,” said Cohren.
“Pack all your personal belongings,” continued Cohren. As a senior lieutenant and executive officer of the company, he was responsible for overseeing and supporting the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. “We won’t be coming back here again. Corporals and lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for the final checks and to pack the morning rations.”
The members of the Exodus Company dispersed quickly. They were part of the second assault troop division, second army. Before they were combined, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was split, which was the main reason why Cohren had mixed feelings about his promotion to senior lieutenant.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first train, walked side by side under the glow of many generator-powered lamps at the forward deployment base. Most had red-tinted glass to avoid detection by enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild-Weasel attacks from the air and ground to counter them.
“A new day and a new task for the Hellhounds,” said Nemic with a dry laugh. “Where are they sending us?”
“A forward deployment base outside Ianlos. We will support the ground attack,” answered Cohren and took a drag on his cigarette. He shared some blame with Craith for starting to smoke, but a year in the field changed you, so he said nothing.
“Shit. Things are always getting worse at the front,” murmured Nemic. “All the news reads: ‘Support war efforts. Send help to the Kurghan Front.’ What about helping the Howland Front?”
“Amen, brother,” said Cohren and flicked the ashes of his cigarette into the mud. “At least we’re making our first armed run and don’t have to run. Captain Shaw should already be there.”
"Did Shaw arrange us a ride?" Nemic asked a bit surprised.
"Yes. He’s actually not as bad as I thought. Not particularly friendly, but one can get along with him."
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone while putting his backpack on. "All units of the Exodus Company meet at the West parking lot when they are ready. We depart with the first armed train at 0500."
In quick succession, he received responses from the squad leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were low-ranking sergeants when they all arrived here. The four had become close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren felt like he knew them forever, even though it was only two years. They were squad leaders, but Craith had been leading the second train for a week now, whose previous leader had been dismissed due to medical reasons after being shot by a Daybreak sniper.
On their way to the parking lot, Cohren and Nemic noticed a group of about eight Kronos battle tanks and four infantry vehicles. Their crews were wandering around, ensuring their machines were ready for action. Quickly, Cohren spotted Captain Boradin Shaw speaking with the commander of the armed train. As they approached, Shaw looked over at them and came towards them, always with an expressionless face.
"Leutnant Nemic... Leutnant Valturi..." He said, noting that Cohren was slower, while looking at Cohren's pistol holster and then looking up again. "Is the company ready, I assume?"
